> - Framework-specific requirements (Angular, React, etc.)
> - CSP policies in place

### XSS Types

- **Reflected XSS**: Malicious code in link, executed when victim clicks
- **Stored XSS**: Malicious code stored on server, executes on page access
- **DOM-based XSS**: Code executed in browser, not sent to server

### Proof of Concept Best Practices

**Use `alert(document.domain)` or `alert(window.origin)` instead of `alert(1)`** to verify execution scope:
```html
<script>alert(document.domain.concat("\n").concat(window.origin))</script>
```

**For stored XSS, use `console.log()` instead of `alert()`** to avoid popup spam:
```html
<script>console.log("XSS from page XYZ\n".concat(document.domain))</script>
```

**Debugger payload (no popup):**
```javascript
<script>debugger;</script>
```

